{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}
A '''Single Screen''' game perspective can apply to all video games in which the entire playfield is shown on the screen, and the player character is unable to move beyond the boundaries of the screen either to a) scroll the game world (e.g. [[Mappy]]), or b) move to a different screen (e.g. [[Berzerk (video game)|Berzerk]]). It is not to be confused with the [[Diorama (game perspective)|diorama]] perspective, which refers to non-screen based games ([[shooting range#Shooting gallery|shooting galleries]], [[pinball]] and other mechanical games) which were popular before and during the early years of video games. Also not to be confused with hybrid perspective games such as Caveman (Gottlieb), and [[Boot Hill (video game)|Boot Hill]] (Midway), which because of their dual camera nature are harder to classify into one perspective. [[File:Pong.png|thumbnail|left|Single Screen]]
==History== Single Screen video games became popular in the early 1970s with [[Pong]]. They offered a simpler and more affordable alternative to the expensive electro mechanical games of the time (such as Sega's Periscope).<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Ultimate History of Video Games: From Pong to Pokémon and Beyond : the Story Behind the Craze that Touched Our Lives and Changed the World|url = https://books.google.co.za/books/about/The_Ultimate_History_of_Video_Games.html?id=C2MH05ogU9oC&redir_esc=y|publisher = Prima Pub.|date = 2001-01-01|isbn = 9780761536437|language = en|first = Steve L.|last = Kent}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title = The Ultimate History of Video Games: from Pong to Pokemon and beyond...the story behind the craze that touched our li ves and changed the world|url = https://books.google.co.za/books?id=PTrcTeAqeaEC&pg=PT469&lpg=PT469&dq=periscope++sega+1295&source=bl&ots=amEv-8_Yfe&sig=g-GkfQ8s4JjjzwuDKvFnFxb8Ojo&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher = Crown/Archetype|date = 2010-06-16|isbn = 9780307560872|language = en|first = Steven|last = Kent}}</ref> The limitations of these early games though was their lack of color and three dimensional effects compared to other games like [[Sonar (arcade game)|Sonar]]. In spite of these limitations single screen games were made covering multiple genres, including racing ([[Gran Trak 10]]), vehicle combat ([[Tank (video game)|Tank]]), shooting galleries ([[Qwak!]]), evasion / collection ([[Shark Jaws]]), and multiplayer shooters ([[Western Gun]]). In contrast to Pinball though (which could offer many more minutes per play) these games were still lacking, due to either their timed play mechanics (through a clock or limited ammunition).<ref>{{Cite web|title = Tracer - Videogame by Sega|url = http://www.arcade-museum.com/game_detail.php?game_id=12739|website = www.arcade-museum.com|accessdate = 2015-08-10}}</ref> One of the earliest Arcade games to move beyond these limitations was [[Breakout (video game)|Breakout]], and when it was released in 1976 it would go on to inspire [[Space Invaders]], the second game to offer a much longer play time than what was common in this game perspective. The next big evolution in this game perspective was then the introduction of multiple screen types ([[Donkey Kong]]) and randomized elements in combination with destructible environments ([[Asteroids (video game)|Asteroids]]) to add not only duration, but greater variety in the single screen experience.
