{{Use British English|date=July 2015}} {{Infobox book | italic title = <!--(see above)--> | name = Streetlife: The untold history of Europe's twentieth century | image = File:Streetlife, The untold history of Europe's twentieth century.jpg | image_size = 200px | alt = | caption = | author = Leif Jerram | audio_read_by = | country = United Kingdom | language = English | series = | release_number = | subject = History of urban Europe | set_in = Europe | published = [[Oxford]] | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | publisher2 = | pub_date = 2011 | media_type = Print (hardback, paperback) | pages = 477 | awards = | isbn = 9780192807076 | oclc = | dewey = 940.097320904 | congress = }}
'''''Streetlife: The untold history of Europe's twentieth century''''' is a 2011 book by [[British people|British]] academic Leif Jerram.
==Synopsis== The book investigates the transformation of Europe from the street level 'from riot and revolution to sporting culture and sexual adventure'.
==Reception== In ''[[The Independent]]'' Christopher Hirst described the work as 'lively'<ref>https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/streetlife-by-leif-jerram-8609978.html</ref> and in ''[[The Financial Times]]'' the book was praised as an 'enjoyably idiosyncratic and provocative journey'.<ref>http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/89284d6e-7766-11e0-824c-00144feabdc0.html</ref> A lengthy review was also published in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]''<ref>http://www.the-tls.co.uk/tls/public/article706981.ece</ref> where the book was described as an 'unromanticised, sweeping and informed cultural history of European cities in the long twentieth century'.
